So, what do I want to say?

00:38:59.270 --> 00:39:00.270
Yeah.

00:39:00.270 --> 00:39:04.970
You were talking about bringing, expanding
the offering for things like electrical engineering.

00:39:04.970 --> 00:39:05.990
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: Right.

00:39:05.990 --> 00:39:10.230
&gt;&gt;Male #2: And there are now online courses
like those from MITx--

00:39:10.230 --> 00:39:11.230
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: Right.

00:39:11.230 --> 00:39:13.270
&gt;&gt;Male #2: which are making a follow into
this.

00:39:13.270 --> 00:39:14.310
Can you make use of this?

00:39:14.310 --> 00:39:16.480
Would it help what you are doing?

00:39:16.480 --> 00:39:17.480
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: Yeah.

00:39:17.480 --> 00:39:26.040
I mean, our faculty look at MIT OpenCourseWare
quite a bit.

00:39:26.040 --> 00:39:30.510
We have a relationship with those guys where
we actually even get a local copy of it.

00:39:30.510 --> 00:39:31.920
So, they take snapshots.

00:39:31.920 --> 00:39:39.400
So, we actually have locally hosted OpenCourseWare
on campus.

00:39:39.400 --> 00:39:43.770
And I can tell you that as we're designing
the electrical engineering program, that's

00:39:43.770 --> 00:39:49.359
one of the sources that we've looked at to
guide us.

00:39:49.359 --> 00:39:50.789
[pause]

00:39:50.789 --> 00:39:55.089
&gt;&gt;Male #3: Hi.

00:39:55.089 --> 00:40:00.039
With only a few percent of the people who
are of a suitable age to go to college, going

00:40:00.039 --> 00:40:07.920
to college, I can see how a step in the quality
of education and the ethics of education can

00:40:07.920 --> 00:40:10.660
make a real contribution to society.

00:40:10.660 --> 00:40:17.930
But in places like the US where lots of people
go to college and ethics is on the decline,

00:40:17.930 --> 00:40:19.650
what strategy can we adopt?

00:40:19.650 --> 00:40:20.650
[laughter]

00:40:20.650 --> 00:40:23.080
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: OK.

00:40:23.080 --> 00:40:24.800
So, look.

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:36.329
I think that the United States and other advanced
countries need to never forget the basics.

00:40:36.329 --> 00:40:37.500
OK?

00:40:37.500 --> 00:40:49.599
I think that there's some classical ideas
that sometimes, as we pursue technology and

00:40:49.599 --> 00:40:57.369
advancement, we start to think that Plato's
"Republic," or "The Allegory of the Cave"

00:40:57.369 --> 00:41:00.440
and things like this no longer apply.

00:41:00.440 --> 00:41:03.280
But there's some ideas that really are timeless.

00:41:03.280 --> 00:41:11.980
And I think that it's very important that
all institutions of learning pay attention

00:41:11.980 --> 00:41:19.369
to the idea that ethics is important and that
civic engagement is important.

00:41:19.369 --> 00:41:26.930
I would also like to say that there is a dark
side in the world.

00:41:26.930 --> 00:41:33.520
And those guys, they have no qualms about
indoctrinating people with bad ideas.

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:34.670
OK?

00:41:34.670 --> 00:41:44.340
And the way to counter that is to make sure
that we are lighting up people's minds with

00:41:44.340 --> 00:41:51.630
the basic things, those timeless ideas.

00:41:51.630 --> 00:42:02.430
Venture capital, this whole model of financing
young people and having patient capital and

00:42:02.430 --> 00:42:07.809
putting money into a company without a lot
of collateral or any collateral, that wouldn't

00:42:07.809 --> 00:42:11.390
work if there was no trust.

00:42:11.390 --> 00:42:17.839
You need a high-trust environment for this
whole phenomenon to be successful, right?

00:42:17.839 --> 00:42:20.540
So that's my view of it.

00:42:20.540 --> 00:42:21.540
[pause]

00:42:21.540 --> 00:42:22.540
Hi, Brigitte.

00:42:22.540 --> 00:42:25.500
&gt;&gt;Female #3: How are you?

00:42:25.500 --> 00:42:27.360
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: Good.

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:30.470
&gt;&gt;Female #3: I have a few questions.

00:42:30.470 --> 00:42:35.880
One, given the kind of environment in Ghana
in terms of employment, you mentioned that

00:42:35.880 --> 00:42:38.099
100 percent of the students get employment.

00:42:38.099 --> 00:42:40.550
Curious about where that is?

00:42:40.550 --> 00:42:45.650
I know that a lot of the traditional companies,
the tel-cos and the banks, tend to dominate.

00:42:45.650 --> 00:42:46.900
And in that environment, two things.

00:42:46.900 --> 00:42:48.750
Do you think that they're able to make change?

00:42:48.750 --> 00:42:53.020
Like, do you think that they are having an
impact outside of themselves?

00:42:53.020 --> 00:42:58.020
Only because the hierarchical nature of the
environment basically says you're small, you

00:42:58.020 --> 00:43:01.049
be quiet, this is how we operate.

00:43:01.049 --> 00:43:02.130
The other side is compensation.

00:43:02.130 --> 00:43:05.650
So, I know compensation varies incredibly
drastically in Ghana.

00:43:05.650 --> 00:43:06.650
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: Right.

00:43:06.650 --> 00:43:10.010
&gt;&gt;Female #3: So, understanding, do you see
your students being rewarded more on the compensation

00:43:10.010 --> 00:43:11.010
side?

00:43:11.010 --> 00:43:14.960
'Cause I think that's gonna be a big factor
in keeping them local in the long term and

00:43:14.960 --> 00:43:15.960
not going to Nigeria.

00:43:15.960 --> 00:43:16.960
[laughs]

00:43:16.960 --> 00:43:17.960
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: Right.

00:43:17.960 --> 00:43:23.369
So, those are very good questions.

00:43:23.369 --> 00:43:31.380
So, we see our students actually climbing
up the corporate ladder wherever they go quite

00:43:31.380 --> 00:43:33.750
quickly.

00:43:33.750 --> 00:43:38.550
And I assume that increased compensation goes
with that.

00:43:38.550 --> 00:43:43.140
So, I think that resolves itself.

00:43:43.140 --> 00:43:51.799
I talk with chief executives in the country
who have now decided that Ashesi is going

00:43:51.799 --> 00:44:00.010
to be a key place to hire from, particularly
because they're engaged with succession planning.

00:44:00.010 --> 00:44:06.520
And they're looking for people that they think
can rise up into middle management and eventually,

00:44:06.520 --> 00:44:07.619
into executive management.

00:44:07.619 --> 00:44:12.020
And they think Ashesi is a place that they
can get those kinds of people.

00:44:12.020 --> 00:44:14.430
So, that's encouraging.

00:44:14.430 --> 00:44:21.289
Those are very encouraging conversations for
me to have.

00:44:21.289 --> 00:44:25.650
Your other question had to do with jobs, right?

00:44:25.650 --> 00:44:30.990
And again, I think it comes down to the basics.

00:44:30.990 --> 00:44:40.319
If somebody is well-educated and is a problem-solver
and has an entrepreneurial mind, and you put

00:44:40.319 --> 00:44:47.839
that person even in a corporate structure,
they will come up with new ideas, new ways

00:44:47.839 --> 00:44:49.849
for the organization to grow.

00:44:49.849 --> 00:44:59.690
And so, for example, when an Ashesi alum goes
and works in a bank and goes to their manager

00:44:59.690 --> 00:45:04.240
and says, "There's this whole population of
people who are unbanked.

00:45:04.240 --> 00:45:08.450
And we need to be thinking of a strategy to
reach those guys."

00:45:08.450 --> 00:45:11.650
And managers convince management to pursue
that.

00:45:11.650 --> 00:45:14.490
Now, that bank is growing, right?

00:45:14.490 --> 00:45:22.170
It's now expanding to look at a segment, a
market segment, that they hadn't before just

00:45:22.170 --> 00:45:26.839
because of this one person who had the idea.

00:45:26.839 --> 00:45:32.390
And as it enters in that segment, they'll
be jobs that come with that.

00:45:32.390 --> 00:45:42.970
Recently, GE entered Ghana and they hired
from Ashesi to open up their Accra office.

00:45:42.970 --> 00:45:48.080
And now, the company is working multimillion
dollar deals in the country.

00:45:48.080 --> 00:45:53.180
And that's going to generate more jobs in
Ghana.

00:45:53.180 --> 00:46:02.589
And so, when I started this project, I said
to myself, "This is a long-term play.

00:46:02.589 --> 00:46:06.890
It's gonna take a couple of decades or maybe
three decades for me to see the full impact

00:46:06.890 --> 00:46:10.150
of the work that we're doing."

00:46:10.150 --> 00:46:14.549
In the meantime, just paying attention to
what are the steps that we're taking and what

00:46:14.549 --> 00:46:17.610
are the little glimmers that we're on the
right path?

00:46:17.610 --> 00:46:23.049
And I think that it's, so far it looks promising.

00:46:23.049 --> 00:46:26.069
[pause]

00:46:26.069 --> 00:46:35.130
&gt;&gt;Male #4: Hello.

00:46:35.130 --> 00:46:38.040
I'm interested in knowing more about your
students.

00:46:38.040 --> 00:46:41.069
What are the criteria to get into Ashesi?

00:46:41.069 --> 00:46:47.369
And what barriers do they face during their
education that might prevent them from graduating

00:46:47.369 --> 00:46:49.190
and being successful in a college?

00:46:49.190 --> 00:46:54.750
And what, how does the college help them achieve
that success?

00:46:54.750 --> 00:46:57.089
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: OK.

00:46:57.089 --> 00:47:00.640
So, Ashesi student body is very diverse.

00:47:00.640 --> 00:47:07.010
So, we have students from poor, rural villages
or even urban slums.

00:47:07.010 --> 00:47:09.799
We have students from quite affluent families
and everything in-between.

00:47:09.799 --> 00:47:15.540
So, it's very dispersed.

00:47:15.540 --> 00:47:22.200
Now, their academic background, as you might
imagine, is different, right?

00:47:22.200 --> 00:47:29.960
So, the kid who grew up in a rural village
went to an under-resourced school, maybe went

00:47:29.960 --> 00:47:32.650
to a school and didn't even have a math teacher.

00:47:32.650 --> 00:47:36.540
It's at a disadvantage.

00:47:36.540 --> 00:47:43.859
When we make admissions decisions, what we
do is we look at a standardized national exam

00:47:43.859 --> 00:47:48.369
and the accreditation board has minimum standards
for admission.

00:47:48.369 --> 00:47:53.920
We certainly will not go below those standards.

00:47:53.920 --> 00:47:56.779
But more importantly, we look at the person.

00:47:56.779 --> 00:47:59.880
So, we do interviews.

00:47:59.880 --> 00:48:01.690
Students write essays.

00:48:01.690 --> 00:48:05.250
We try to really understand who this person
is.

00:48:05.250 --> 00:48:15.619
And the idea is, the kid who's self-taught
and got a "C" in math is often just as bright

00:48:15.619 --> 00:48:18.079
as a kid who went to a really good school
and got an "A" in math.

00:48:18.079 --> 00:48:21.300
They just didn't have the resources.

00:48:21.300 --> 00:48:25.309
And we need to give that person an opportunity.

00:48:25.309 --> 00:48:28.119
And we need to provide the resources to help
that person.

00:48:28.119 --> 00:48:34.460
So, for example, having a learning lab where
they can go and get extra help with math and

00:48:34.460 --> 00:48:36.700
English and things like that.

00:48:36.700 --> 00:48:41.539
Those things are very important to help people
get through.

00:48:41.539 --> 00:48:42.809
Now, once they're--.

00:48:42.809 --> 00:48:47.410
So, that's part of the answer to the second
part of your question.

00:48:47.410 --> 00:48:58.020
One of the things that prevent people from
being successful in college, interestingly,

00:48:58.020 --> 00:49:02.809
some of our students who have struggled the
most are from quite affluent backgrounds.

00:49:02.809 --> 00:49:07.210
And part of the reason they struggle when
they're in college is because they just don't

00:49:07.210 --> 00:49:10.210
have that fire in their belly.

00:49:10.210 --> 00:49:12.299
The stakes are not as high.

00:49:12.299 --> 00:49:14.650
They're not as driven.

00:49:14.650 --> 00:49:16.160
And sometimes, that's a problem.

00:49:16.160 --> 00:49:19.069
And so, that's something that we're grappling
with.

00:49:19.069 --> 00:49:23.460
So, you'll have a few students who will flunk
out academically.

00:49:23.460 --> 00:49:32.930
There's some students who will be expelled
for ethics violations if they do it enough.

00:49:32.930 --> 00:49:39.960
There's always a second chance given to people,
depending on the severity of the offense.

00:49:39.960 --> 00:49:42.860
But so, we have a few people that fall into
that category.

00:49:42.860 --> 00:49:47.490
It's something that we have to do to just
make the point that, "Hey, this is who we

00:49:47.490 --> 00:49:49.710
are."

00:49:49.710 --> 00:49:55.400
And then, there's a third group that's very
difficult to deal with.

00:49:55.400 --> 00:50:00.710
When we give financial aid, and we give a
significant amount of financial aid every

00:50:00.710 --> 00:50:07.859
year, but what we do is we commit all the
financial aid dollars we have available upon

00:50:07.859 --> 00:50:08.859
entry.

00:50:08.859 --> 00:50:12.440
In fact, it's never enough, OK?

00:50:12.440 --> 00:50:19.500
And then, after the fact, it may be a couple
of years in, as students' family circumstances

00:50:19.500 --> 00:50:22.490
change, they can no longer afford the fees.

00:50:22.490 --> 00:50:27.490
There are a few students who drop out because
their families are no longer able to afford

00:50:27.490 --> 00:50:28.490
the fees.

00:50:28.490 --> 00:50:34.780
And that's very difficult, but it is what
it is.

00:50:34.780 --> 00:50:36.160
I mean, we need--.

00:50:36.160 --> 00:50:43.220
One of the things that we're trying to do
is to raise extra money, sort of emergency

00:50:43.220 --> 00:50:49.720
funding, and the executive team at Ashesi
set up an executive emergency fund that we

00:50:49.720 --> 00:50:51.990
contribute to ourselves.

00:50:51.990 --> 00:50:54.540
And certain categories of students.

00:50:54.540 --> 00:51:02.029
If there's been a death in the family, a parent
has died, or there's some other major incident

00:51:02.029 --> 00:51:05.849
like that, they can apply to that fund to
get funding.

00:51:05.849 --> 00:51:09.470
But again, even that funding is limited, right?

00:51:09.470 --> 00:51:11.570
So, those are the things that cause problems.

00:51:11.570 --> 00:51:12.570
[pause]

00:51:12.570 --> 00:51:16.020
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: I think we have time for
one last question.

00:51:16.020 --> 00:51:17.500
&gt;&gt;Female #3: I'm last?

00:51:17.500 --> 00:51:18.500
OK.

00:51:18.500 --> 00:51:19.940
So, you talked about wanting to change a continent.

00:51:19.940 --> 00:51:21.119
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: Mm-hmm.

00:51:21.119 --> 00:51:25.530
&gt;&gt;Female #3: So, what are your ideas for making
Ashesi scale?

00:51:25.530 --> 00:51:30.829
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: The big scale question.

00:51:30.829 --> 00:51:41.859
Well, let me say that, first of all, when
I started Ashesi, I had this idea that one

00:51:41.859 --> 00:51:45.910
day there would be like, ten Ashesi's in Africa.

00:51:45.910 --> 00:51:50.599
And franchise is not the right word because
we're not for profit.

00:51:50.599 --> 00:51:58.490
But there would be family of schools around
the continent that have the same mission,

00:51:58.490 --> 00:52:05.859
they share the same ethos, that perhaps operate
differently depending in terms of particular

00:52:05.859 --> 00:52:09.980
courses they offer, depending on where they
are on the continent.

00:52:09.980 --> 00:52:13.720
And I was gonna be the one to make it happen,
OK?

00:52:13.720 --> 00:52:16.230
So, then I got started.

00:52:16.230 --> 00:52:21.230
And believe me, [laughs] it is really hard.

00:52:21.230 --> 00:52:27.289
So, what we, where we are now is to say, "OK.

00:52:27.289 --> 00:52:32.180
We've done the first phase of our project,
the first ten years."

00:52:32.180 --> 00:52:35.140
Hugely successful in my view.

00:52:35.140 --> 00:52:42.640
And we're doing the second phase, which is
about really identifying a few very high-impact

00:52:42.640 --> 00:52:51.900
areas that if we do will be transformative
in Ghana--just public, private.

00:52:51.900 --> 00:52:56.010
And then to say, "Well, we're going to invite
students from all over the continent to experience

00:52:56.010 --> 00:52:57.010
this."

00:52:57.010 --> 00:52:59.430
And they'll go back to their countries and
make change.

00:52:59.430 --> 00:53:00.510
We have examples of this.

00:53:00.510 --> 00:53:04.960
We have someone who went back to Liberia who
is making a big difference.

00:53:04.960 --> 00:53:08.539
There's somebody who went back to Sierra Leone
who is making a huge difference.

00:53:08.539 --> 00:53:10.770
And just expand it that way.

00:53:10.770 --> 00:53:17.650
Now, once we've built the model, then the
question is how do we take that and scale

00:53:17.650 --> 00:53:19.010
it.

00:53:19.010 --> 00:53:20.369
OK?

00:53:20.369 --> 00:53:27.490
And it's dawned on me that the way to take
it and scale it is I need to build up my organization.

00:53:27.490 --> 00:53:35.930
We actually need focused minds on how do you
take this and replicate it?

00:53:35.930 --> 00:53:44.750
And depending on funding levels and so on,
we may or may not need other Patricks to execute

00:53:44.750 --> 00:53:45.750
this.

00:53:45.750 --> 00:53:47.940
And I think that the leadership is really
important.

00:53:47.940 --> 00:53:55.580
Now, this one has been super difficult because
funding was very scarce when we started.

00:53:55.580 --> 00:54:03.440
It required somebody who was absolutely dedicated
and persistent and willing to go through a

00:54:03.440 --> 00:54:08.319
bunch of stuff.

00:54:08.319 --> 00:54:10.329
Those people are hard to find.

00:54:10.329 --> 00:54:15.619
But, and so, those projects need to go through
that same pain.

00:54:15.619 --> 00:54:22.791
Then, we will need to find people in those
countries that have that persistence and that

00:54:22.791 --> 00:54:27.440
dedication, who are gonna go through the pain
to get it done.

00:54:27.440 --> 00:54:28.740
It's gonna be crucial.

00:54:28.740 --> 00:54:32.599
And it's hard to find those guys.

00:54:32.599 --> 00:54:37.160
Now, if there's funding for it, then it may
be different.

00:54:37.160 --> 00:54:40.059
But I haven't figured it all out yet.

00:54:40.059 --> 00:54:44.810
But it would be really cool if we could replicate
Ashesi.

00:54:44.810 --> 00:54:50.150
So, that's why the second answer is replicating
the idea.

00:54:50.150 --> 00:54:57.410
So, there's replicating what we've done and
there is looking at other institutions that

00:54:57.410 --> 00:55:02.990
already exist, that already have infrastructure,
that already have people, and say, "Can we,

00:55:02.990 --> 00:55:09.790
is there a way that we can inject the Ashesi
DNA, the Ashesi ethos into those institutions?"

00:55:09.790 --> 00:55:15.210
And that also is gonna require sitting down
and thinking about exactly how we do that.

00:55:15.210 --> 00:55:27.490
But those are the two ways that, I think,
eventually we will look at the scale question.

00:55:27.490 --> 00:55:40.032
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Thank you, everyone.

00:55:40.032 --> 00:55:41.032
Thank you so much for coming, Patrick.

00:55:41.032 --> 00:55:42.032
I know there are a lot of--.

00:55:42.032 --> 00:55:43.032
Some of you have meetings throughout the afternoon.

00:55:43.032 --> 00:55:44.032
If you don't have that time scheduled and
you want to try and find some time, come see

00:55:44.032 --> 00:55:45.032
me afterwards.

00:55:45.032 --> 00:55:46.032
And I'll thank you again.

00:55:46.032 --> 00:55:47.032
&gt;&gt;Patrick Awuah: Thank you very much.

00:55:47.032 --> 00:55:47.033
[applause]

